multi profile routing implementation plan

For Hermes: Use subagent-driven-development skill to implement this plan task-by-task.
Goal: Enable a single Gateway process to serve multiple profiles simultaneously via per-user/per-chat profile bindings, eliminating the need to restart the gateway to switch profiles.
Architecture: Add a profile_bindings table to state.db, retrofit GatewayRunner to maintain per-profile agent caches, and inject profile resolution into _handle_message → _run_agent. Profile resolution follows priority: per-user binding &gt; per-chat binding &gt; gateway default.
Tech Stack: Python 3.12+, SQLite (state.db, schema v11→v12 migration), asyncio

Overview
This plan modifies the Gateway to internally route incoming messages to the correct
profile’s AIAgent, instead of binding the entire Gateway process to a single
INTELLECT_HOME at startup.  The existing single-profile path is preserved as a
degraded fallback: when no bindings exist or multi_profile.enabled is falsy,
the Gateway continues to use its own INTELLECT_HOME exactly as before.
Key design decisions


Profile resolution lives in gateway/profile_router.py — a new dedicated module
that queries state.db for bindings and merges per-profile configs.  This keeps the
routing concern separate from the existing 17,000-line gateway/run.py.


AIAgent cache becomes dict[str, OrderedDict] — keyed by profile_name first,
then session_key.  The existing _AGENT_CACHE_MAX_SIZE and _AGENT_CACHE_IDLE_TTL
apply per-profile, so a busy profile doesn’t evict agents from an idle one.


Config merging follows deep_merge() — the per-profile config.yaml is loaded
on first use and shallow-merged with the Gateway’s own config, with profile values
taking precedence.  This means a profile can override its model, system prompt,
toolsets, and memory settings independently.


State.db schema v12 adds one new table (profile_bindings) with zero
migration risk — the migration is an additive CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS.


What does NOT change

Gateway startup / shutdown lifecycle — same start_gateway(), same PID file,
same lock scoping under INTELLECT_HOME.
SessionStore / SessionDB — sessions remain scoped to INTELLECT_HOME, not
profile.  This is intentional: the Gateway host is the session owner, and
profiles are an agent-configuration concern.
Kanban dispatcher — _default_spawn() already passes -p &lt;assignee&gt; to
subprocess invocations.  No changes needed.
CLI / intellect chat — profile switching via -p &lt;name&gt; is unchanged.

